With all the recent discussion of artificial intelligence — and with Anthropic releasing the Claude Fable 5 model today — I began to wonder: Is artificial intelligence actually intelligent? Not in the sense of performing pattern recognition and calculations to come up with new ways of understanding things, but can it generate original thought — something like the panopticon, or a new art project? I gave it a simple request:

“Humans, we think about things… we think about our problems… we think about what occurs… we think about how to make our lives more efficient or better or how to do less work with less energy and get more money… we do this… sometimes we just look at a mountain and go wouldn’t it be great to go up there? And most great thought comes from the consideration of what we know juxtaposed against our environment… so I want you as an AI to do exactly that… think, consider, and come up with an original idea…”

The responses may surprise you and make you think about what it means to be human versus machine.

Claude Opus 4.8 went very metaphysical, sounding like an older teen or a young monk contemplating life and the nature of machine life versus human life.

Claude Fable 5 exhibited the developmental behavior of a 17-to-29-year-old, but it did come up with a novel way of thinking about the ordinary moments in human lives and how our perception is limited by our inability to perceive the events of our lives in full — events it thinks it may be better equipped to perceive, mirror back, and learn from.

Both focused not on what they could do for their own lives, but on how they could better understand humanity. If we are the ones trying to figure out what AI is, AI wants to know what we are, too. Who is using whom?

Please keep in mind: this is not a test of sentience, but of a machine’s reasoning capabilities and how it can use reasoning to come up with novel concepts beyond mathematical patterns and formulas. Below are full copies of both responses:

